laboratory_examinations.findings: A 2.3 cm hypodensity in the right hepatic lobe is a simple cyst. An adjacent slightly enhancing 9mm hypodensity likely represents an adjacent hemangioma. The kidneys enhance symmetrically and excrete contrast promptly without hydronephrosis. Tiny hypodensities in the kidneys bilaterally are likely cysts. The appendix is dilated to 7 mm with wall hyperenhancement and surrounding stranding.
